WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.280
Hi, my name is Chelsea Parlett-Pelleriti and I'm on Twitter at Chelsea Parlett in case

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:15.440
you want to follow any of the fun stats content that I make.

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:19.799
And speaking of stats content, something that I've spent a lot of time making in the past

00:00:19.799 --> 00:00:23.280
year are guided simulation exercises.

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:29.639
I teach data science to mostly undergraduates and it can be an intimidating subject to them.

00:00:29.639 --> 00:00:35.119
I often get asked for rules of thumb that they can use to make good data science decisions.

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:40.799
And while there are some rules of thumb that work in a lot of situations, I want my students

00:00:40.799 --> 00:00:46.520
to come away with a deep understanding of the concepts so that when they're in a situation

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:50.599
where that rule of thumb doesn't apply, they're not just stuck.

00:00:50.599 --> 00:00:57.040
I decided that guided simulation exercises were a great way to create that deeper understanding.

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:02.840
By my definition, guided simulation exercises are activities where you're asked to simulate

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:09.120
data, you apply an algorithm or a computation to that data, and then you're given specific

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:14.440
guided questions that can help you figure out what that simulation can tell you about

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:19.239
whichever algorithm or computation you applied to the data.

00:01:19.239 --> 00:01:22.320
Simulation exercises are helpful for three main reasons.

00:01:22.639 --> 00:01:28.040
First, I think it encourages this attitude of exploration when learning.

00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:33.839
And second, it gives you tools to test your intuition or try weird edge cases that you

00:01:33.839 --> 00:01:36.800
think of and see what happens.

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:43.120
And finally, I think it empowers this deep understanding of the concepts that you're learning.

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:48.760
A lot of people learn data science because they think they should, but my goal is to

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:53.559
help people really deeply explore the concepts that they're learning.

00:01:53.559 --> 00:01:59.480
And sure, they could write their own simulations, but I think the guided part is really important.

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:04.040
I think these exercises are a little more practical than just throwing people in the

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:06.279
deep end on their own.

00:02:06.279 --> 00:02:13.759
It makes simulating data in R feel more approachable, and it gives people tools to try and figure

00:02:13.759 --> 00:02:17.479
things out themselves rather than just relying on what they're told.

00:02:17.479 --> 00:02:24.039
Relatedly, the guided nature of these exercises gives people the tools to learn and try things

00:02:24.039 --> 00:02:29.960
on their own and tailor their experience to things that specifically make them curious.

00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:33.880
For example, maybe you're wondering, what would happen if I ran principal component

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:38.279
analysis on a set of variables that are completely uncorrelated?

00:02:38.279 --> 00:02:40.279
Well, try it out.

00:02:40.279 --> 00:02:46.039
Or maybe you're wondering why we would ever use k-fold cross-validation rather than the

00:02:46.119 --> 00:02:50.039
simpler, more computationally efficient train-test split.

00:02:50.039 --> 00:02:54.360
Well, run a bunch of simulations and see what the difference is.

00:02:54.360 --> 00:02:59.320
In my opinion, the best data scientists are the ones who have a little bit of doubt about

00:02:59.320 --> 00:03:04.600
whether the established method is the best way, necessarily.

00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:11.720
And these guided simulation exercises encourage people to test things out, to push on the

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:16.919
boundaries of established methods, and to figure out how our favorite algorithms work

00:03:16.919 --> 00:03:19.559
in atypical situations.

00:03:19.559 --> 00:03:23.800
After all, our data will not always be well-behaved.

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:29.080
Guided simulation exercises are not a replacement for the math and theory that go behind data

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:32.759
science topics, but it can help support them.

00:03:32.759 --> 00:03:39.399
And I think the examples, the specific questions, and the established code help make simulation

00:03:39.399 --> 00:03:44.520
more accessible, especially to people who don't have the skills yet or maybe don't have

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:47.800
the time to set all of it up on their own.

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:52.039
I hope you'll check out the guided simulations that are already on the conference GitHub

00:03:52.039 --> 00:03:55.080
and all of the ones that we make in the future.

00:03:55.080 --> 00:04:00.119
But for now, in my last minute, I would love to give you the world's quickest overview

00:04:00.119 --> 00:04:04.360
of my principal component analysis guided simulation exercise.

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:09.720
When I teach principal component analysis, one of the main ideas that I emphasize is

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:15.160
that principal component analysis takes advantage of relationships between variables in order

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:20.679
to create more efficient axes that better define the variation in the data.

00:04:20.679 --> 00:04:25.799
So it shouldn't be a surprise that when we look at principal component analysis on completely

00:04:25.799 --> 00:04:31.239
uncorrelated variables, the screen plot shows us that each variable pretty much contributes

00:04:31.239 --> 00:04:33.480
its own independent information.

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:38.839
On the other hand, when we have highly correlated variables, the PCA model as well as the screen

00:04:38.839 --> 00:04:44.440
plot tell us that a lot of the variation then can be explained by one single component because

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:48.200
there was a lot of shared information in the data originally.

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:49.799
Thank you so much for listening to my talk.

00:04:49.799 --> 00:04:53.880
I would love to connect with all of you over the internet and hear whether you use any

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:59.399
of these guided simulation exercises, either for yourself or for people that you teach.

00:04:59.399 --> 00:05:02.679
And definitely let me know if you create any of your own.

00:05:02.679 --> 00:05:04.519
I would love to hear about it.

00:05:04.519 --> 00:05:10.119
Thank you.

